30:58.340 --> 31:00.340
you cobble it onto CO2,

31:00.340 --> 31:02.340
or you're growing like a methanogen in the vent.

31:02.340 --> 31:04.340
The hydrogen is bubbling out of the ground,

31:04.340 --> 31:07.340
you simply cobble it onto CO2.

31:07.340 --> 31:11.340
Life all across Earth is based on the reaction

31:11.340 --> 31:13.340
between hydrogen and CO2.

31:13.340 --> 31:15.340
And we go round eating things,

31:15.340 --> 31:19.340
but we're entirely dependent on the primary producers,

31:19.340 --> 31:21.340
the plants and the bacteria,

31:21.340 --> 31:24.340
which are basically reacting hydrogen with CO2.

31:25.340 --> 31:28.340
Hydrogen and CO2 don't react

31:28.340 --> 31:32.340
except under these rather careful conditions,

31:32.340 --> 31:34.340
where you have structure,

31:34.340 --> 31:36.340
the same kind of structure that we see in cells.

31:36.340 --> 31:39.340
So how common are those conditions likely to be?

31:39.340 --> 31:42.340
On the early Earth, we think that they would have been

31:42.340 --> 31:45.340
basically all the way across the sea floor.

31:45.340 --> 31:48.340
Because it's a reaction between rock and water.

31:48.340 --> 31:52.340
So this is, if you imagine this is the sea floor,

31:52.340 --> 31:55.340
and then down beneath in the crust underneath the sea floor,

31:55.340 --> 32:01.340
these green rocks here are rich in minerals like olivine.

32:01.340 --> 32:04.340
So olivine is iron, magnesium rich rock,

32:04.340 --> 32:06.340
mostly found in the mantle of the Earth today,

32:06.340 --> 32:09.340
which is why you don't see so many reactions like this anymore,

32:09.340 --> 32:12.340
but four billion years ago there wasn't really such a difference

32:12.340 --> 32:14.340
between the mantle and the crust.

32:14.340 --> 32:17.340
So we think these reactions would happen almost everywhere.

32:17.340 --> 32:21.340
The water percolates down to depths of five or six kilometres

32:21.340 --> 32:25.340
beneath the crust, and will react with these rocks.

32:25.340 --> 32:27.340
So if you were to take a lump of olivine

32:27.340 --> 32:29.340
and put it in a bucket of water,

32:29.340 --> 32:32.340
you'd probably get one bubble in about a week's time.

32:32.340 --> 32:34.340
It's not something, you know,

32:34.340 --> 32:37.340
it's not an experiment you want to do for the kids.

32:37.340 --> 32:39.340
But at the higher temperatures and pressures

32:39.340 --> 32:41.340
down at the bottom of the sea floor,

32:41.340 --> 32:44.340
it really is bubbling with hydrogen gas.

32:44.340 --> 32:46.340
It's a pretty vigorous reaction.

32:46.340 --> 32:48.340
And that's really all it takes.

32:48.340 --> 32:51.340
It's the reaction between water and rock

32:51.340 --> 32:54.340
to produce strongly alkaline fluids rich in hydrogen gas.

32:54.340 --> 32:56.340
It's an exothermic reaction,

32:56.340 --> 32:58.340
which means it's producing heat,

32:58.340 --> 33:01.340
and so these are buoyant warm fluids which percolate back up.

33:01.340 --> 33:03.340
And when they get to the sea floor,

33:03.340 --> 33:06.340
they react with the waters of the ocean,

33:06.340 --> 33:09.340
the minerals in the ocean to precipitate as these vents.

33:09.340 --> 33:12.340
So the reaction between rock and water is down below the sea floor,

33:12.340 --> 33:15.340
but the vents themselves are up at the sea floor.

33:15.340 --> 33:19.340
So they should happen on any wet rocky planet.

33:19.340 --> 33:23.340
And there's actually quite a lot of lovely suggestions

33:23.340 --> 33:27.340
from across our own solar system that they do happen.

33:27.340 --> 33:31.340
So Mars, there's traces of methane,

33:31.340 --> 33:33.340
thought to be traces of methane on Mars.

33:33.340 --> 33:35.340
Where does it come from?

33:35.340 --> 33:37.340
The wishful thinkers hope it comes from life.

33:37.340 --> 33:39.340
It's possible it does.

33:39.340 --> 33:42.340
But it's more likely that it comes from exactly this same process

33:42.340 --> 33:45.340
of rocks reacting with water.

33:45.340 --> 33:47.340
There is water on Mars still,

33:47.340 --> 33:50.340
mostly frozen and mostly beneath the surface.

33:50.340 --> 33:54.340
But you're likely to produce hydrogen and methane

33:54.340 --> 33:56.340
for exactly the same reasons.

33:56.340 --> 33:59.340
And we see on Enceladus, for example, or Europa,

33:59.340 --> 34:03.340
which are moons, icy moons, with frozen oceans.

34:03.340 --> 34:07.340
But underneath the frozen ocean on Enceladus and on Europa,

34:07.340 --> 34:10.340
it seems that there is a rather large ocean,

34:10.340 --> 34:13.340
larger than the Earth's oceans.

34:13.340 --> 34:17.340
And these plumes that you can see here

34:17.340 --> 34:20.340
are escaping from the surface of Enceladus.

34:20.340 --> 34:24.340
And they are very alkaline, pH 10, or thereabouts,

34:24.340 --> 34:27.340
and rich in hydrogen, gas and methane.

34:27.340 --> 34:29.340
And so the only thing that we know of,

34:29.340 --> 34:31.340
the only geological process we know of

34:31.340 --> 34:33.340
that could produce an ocean that was that alkaline

34:33.340 --> 34:36.340
and that rich in hydrogen would be this same process.

34:36.340 --> 34:38.340
It's called serpentinisation,

34:38.340 --> 34:40.340
but it's the reaction between olivine and water

34:40.340 --> 34:42.340
to produce a mineral called serpentinite,

34:42.340 --> 34:45.340
which is why it's called serpentinisation.

34:45.340 --> 34:47.340
So even in our own solar system,

34:47.340 --> 34:50.340
there are at least three worlds

34:50.340 --> 34:53.340
where this process is actively going on.

34:53.340 --> 34:55.340
And this is really one of the places

34:55.340 --> 34:59.340
that NASA would most like to go to, me too.

34:59.340 --> 35:02.340
And it actually also means,

35:02.340 --> 35:05.340
because of the politics of these situations,

