Anyway, so that's within our own solar system.

35:47.340 --> 35:51.340
If we go further afield,

35:51.340 --> 35:55.340
there's been a real drive

35:55.340 --> 35:57.340
to discover exoplanets,

35:57.340 --> 36:02.340
planets orbiting distant stars.

36:02.340 --> 36:07.340
And there have been projections now

36:07.340 --> 36:10.340
that there should be something in the order of tens of billions

36:10.340 --> 36:13.340
of Earth-like wet rocky planets

36:13.340 --> 36:16.340
in the Milky Way alone.

36:16.340 --> 36:19.340
So if that's true,

36:19.340 --> 36:22.340
all of these Earth-like wet rocky planets

36:22.340 --> 36:25.340
should be producing the same kind of vents.

36:25.340 --> 36:28.340
Water is basically ubiquitous.

36:28.340 --> 36:31.340
We can detect oliveene in interstellar dust.

36:31.340 --> 36:33.340
It's very common,

36:33.340 --> 36:37.340
so most rocky planets would have a fair amount of oliveene in them.

36:37.340 --> 36:42.340
And CO2, again, is common as an atmospheric gas,

36:42.340 --> 36:45.340
certainly in our own solar system.

36:45.340 --> 36:47.340
So you could imagine that these same conditions

36:47.340 --> 36:51.340
would apply really on a very, very wide scale.

36:51.340 --> 36:53.340
And so life starting elsewhere

36:53.340 --> 36:56.340
may be constrained by the same reasons.

36:56.340 --> 36:59.340
We also require proton gradients across membranes

36:59.340 --> 37:02.340
to get going because the reaction between hydrogen and CO2

37:02.340 --> 37:04.340
is difficult,

37:04.340 --> 37:09.340
and this is a probabilistically simple way of doing it.

37:09.340 --> 37:15.340
So if you were to find, say, a thousand life forms in the universe,

37:15.340 --> 37:18.340
would it be carbon-based or not?

37:18.340 --> 37:20.340
