37:20.340 --> 37:23.340
because carbon is ubiquitous.

37:23.340 --> 37:26.340
It's extremely good at the kind of complex chemistry

37:26.340 --> 37:28.340
that needs to be done.

37:28.340 --> 37:31.340
And it comes in a convenient LEGO brick, CO2.

37:31.340 --> 37:33.340
So you can build large complex molecules

37:33.340 --> 37:35.340
by adding on one brick at a time.

37:35.340 --> 37:37.340
If you start with silicon,

37:37.340 --> 37:40.340
you're starting with silicon oxide, sand.

37:40.340 --> 37:42.340
Don't try and build with sand.

37:42.340 --> 37:44.340
You want to build with LEGO.

37:44.340 --> 37:47.340
And carbon dioxide is a LEGO brick.

37:47.340 --> 37:50.340
And so if you were to find a thousand different life forms,

37:50.340 --> 37:52.340
I would wader a bet that it's going to be carbon-based,

37:52.340 --> 37:54.340
let's say, 995 times out of a thousand,

37:54.340 --> 37:56.340
and something wild and funky,

37:56.340 --> 37:58.340
perhaps the rest of the times.

37:58.340 --> 38:01.340
But carbon is so common, so good at what it does,

38:01.340 --> 38:03.340
and so convenient in the forms in which it comes,

38:03.340 --> 38:06.340
that it would be very surprising if it wasn't carbon-based.

38:06.340 --> 38:08.340
But then we've already run into this constraint.

38:08.340 --> 38:12.340
How do you make carbon dioxide react with CO2?

38:12.340 --> 38:15.340
I would say we're likely to find bacteria

38:15.340 --> 38:18.340
many places throughout the universe.

38:18.340 --> 38:21.340
But what about more complex things than bacteria?

38:21.340 --> 38:23.340
I don't know how many people in this room

38:23.340 --> 38:26.340
