Would we find anything more complex than bacteria?

38:48.340 --> 38:50.340
We need to look back, though,

38:50.340 --> 38:53.340
on what I've accomplished, what I'm suggesting is a set of constraints

38:53.340 --> 38:58.340
that cells anywhere are going to be based on reacting hydrogen with CO2,

38:58.340 --> 39:02.340
and to do it, they're going to need proton gradients across membranes.

39:03.340 --> 39:06.340
And bacteria have remained constrained and haven't changed

39:06.340 --> 39:08.340
for four billion years in their morphology,

39:08.340 --> 39:10.340
neither have archaea.

39:10.340 --> 39:12.340
So could it be that they are constrained

39:12.340 --> 39:16.340
by the way that they generate their energy?

39:16.340 --> 39:19.340
Well, I think that's probably the case.

39:19.340 --> 39:24.340
John Maynard Smith was one of the great evolutionary biologists of the 20th century,

39:24.340 --> 39:27.340
and he was at UCL for a period where I am,

39:27.340 --> 39:30.340
so I think a lot of...

39:30.340 --> 39:34.340
It's a great place, UCL, at least in one sense,

39:34.340 --> 39:38.340
in the sense that some of the greatest thinkers and biologists of the 20th century

39:38.340 --> 39:40.340
worked there for a while.

39:40.340 --> 39:43.340
They all left and went to Cambridge or somewhere after a bit,

39:43.340 --> 39:46.340
but for a while they were all there at UCL,

39:46.340 --> 39:49.340
and I think a lot of us walk around these corridors and think,

39:49.340 --> 39:51.340
oh, JVS Haldane used to walk down here.

39:51.340 --> 39:53.340
I better do something good today.

39:54.340 --> 39:58.340
So Maynard Smith was one of the great evolutionary biologists of the 20th century,

39:58.340 --> 40:01.340
and he liked calling things that shouldn't happen

40:01.340 --> 40:03.340
and evolutionary scandal.

40:03.340 --> 40:05.340
He was scandalised by sex.

40:05.340 --> 40:07.340
Sex really shouldn't happen.

40:07.340 --> 40:10.340
Why wouldn't people not just make clones of themselves instead?

40:10.340 --> 40:13.340
And he spent a lot of his career trying to work out why sex does happen

40:13.340 --> 40:18.340
and why most things that make clones of themselves just fall extinct after a period.

40:18.340 --> 40:23.340
I'd like to think, he never actually said that the eukaryotes were an evolutionary scandal,

40:23.340 --> 40:26.340
but I think he would have seen it in those terms.

40:26.340 --> 40:32.340
The problem is that all complex life is composed of this one cell type,

40:32.340 --> 40:34.340
this eukaryotic cell.

40:34.340 --> 40:39.340
The fact that we all obviously share a common ancestor

40:39.340 --> 40:43.340
because the plants and the animals, if you look at their cells under a microscope,

40:43.340 --> 40:47.340
they're almost indistinguishable in the sense that they all have a nucleus.

40:47.340 --> 40:51.340
They all have lots of membrane systems called the endoplasmic reticulum, for example.

40:51.340 --> 40:54.340
All lysosomes, they all have mitochondria.

40:54.340 --> 40:58.340
You could write page after page in a textbook of things that plants and animals have in common

40:58.340 --> 41:00.340
at the level of cells,

41:00.340 --> 41:03.340
but fungi have the same things in common as well,

41:03.340 --> 41:09.340
and so does an amoeba, or single-celled algae and so on.

41:09.340 --> 41:14.340
It's a shockingly long list, and it's quite baffling as to why that would be the case.

41:14.340 --> 41:20.340
So traits like sex as well, lots of amoeba, in fact pretty much all of them,

41:20.340 --> 41:23.340
are sexual, it turns out.

41:23.340 --> 41:27.340
For a long time we assumed they weren't because you never really caught two of them together.

41:28.340 --> 41:31.340
But now we know their genomes.

41:31.340 --> 41:34.340
Funnily enough, it's the genomes that give insight into these things.

41:34.340 --> 41:37.340
We can see that all the genes that are required for meiosis,

41:37.340 --> 41:41.340
which is to say the recombination part of sex and the cell division,

41:41.340 --> 41:44.340
we find them all in amoeba.

41:44.340 --> 41:47.340
We find them all in very ancient looking cells.

41:47.340 --> 41:50.340
And there's plenty of evidence, again, from the genomes

41:50.340 --> 41:54.340
that they've been recombining genes and changing the structure of the genome continuously.

41:54.340 --> 41:58.340
We know that they're sexual, even if we've never caught them at it.

41:58.340 --> 42:01.340
So this is the scandal then.

42:01.340 --> 42:05.340
All eukaryotic cells share this long list of traits.

42:05.340 --> 42:10.340
Bacteria and archaea just don't do it.

42:10.340 --> 42:12.340
They don't do sex, for example.

42:12.340 --> 42:15.340
They pass genes around a bit, they do some recombination,

42:15.340 --> 42:18.340
but they don't fuse cells together, line up whole genomes,

42:18.340 --> 42:23.340
cross across genes and then separate up, and bacteria just don't do that.

42:23.340 --> 42:28.340
So the scandal, if all of these traits, and there's hundreds and hundreds of them,

42:28.340 --> 42:31.340
evolve by natural selection, step by step,

42:31.340 --> 42:34.340
and there's no reason to imagine that that didn't happen,

42:34.340 --> 42:39.340
and each of these small steps offered some kind of an advantage,

42:39.340 --> 42:42.340
and again, there's no reason to assume that that's not true,

42:42.340 --> 42:48.340
then why is it that none of them evolve in the bacteria or the archaea for the same reasons?

42:48.340 --> 42:50.340
They really ought to, but they don't.

42:50.340 --> 42:53.340
So you could think of eyes as a nice example.

42:53.340 --> 42:56.340
Lots of creationists say what use is half an eye,

