Any thoughts?

47:12.340 --> 47:14.340
Twice the amount of humans.

47:14.340 --> 47:16.340
Exactly, twice the amount of humans.

47:16.340 --> 47:19.340
40,000 genes.

47:19.340 --> 47:22.340
Now maybe we do lots of additional regulation,

47:22.340 --> 47:24.340
or maybe we're just not very much more complicated

47:24.340 --> 47:26.340
than paramecium.

47:26.340 --> 47:30.340
By most objective measures of complexity,

47:30.340 --> 47:32.340
there's not a great world of difference

47:32.340 --> 47:34.340
between these two types of cell,

47:34.340 --> 47:36.340
in terms of the number of genes,

47:36.340 --> 47:38.340
in terms of the amount of morphological complexity,

47:38.340 --> 47:41.340
in terms of basically the hard wiring of it.

47:41.340 --> 47:45.340
The real difference is between bacteria and single cell eukaryotes,

47:45.340 --> 47:48.340
rather than between single cell eukaryotes

47:48.340 --> 47:53.340
and large multicellular organisms.

47:53.340 --> 47:56.340
I'm going to have to, rather than exploring all the possible options,

47:56.340 --> 47:59.340
I'm going to tell you what I think the answer is.

47:59.340 --> 48:02.340
We could be here all the rest of the week.

48:02.340 --> 48:06.340
Here's a group of cells that are pretty simple,

48:06.340 --> 48:08.340
as eukaryotes go.

48:08.340 --> 48:10.340
This is jardia.

48:10.340 --> 48:12.340
Jardia causes explosive diarrhea,

48:12.340 --> 48:15.340
that anybody who's been walking in the mountains in America,

48:15.340 --> 48:18.340
may have had jardial poisoning.

48:18.340 --> 48:20.340
I never had it,

48:20.340 --> 48:23.340
but when I used to go walking in the mountains in places like that,

48:23.340 --> 48:26.340
I used to be terrified that when I drank from the mountain streams,

48:26.340 --> 48:28.340
I would get it.

48:28.340 --> 48:31.340
But it doesn't have any mitochondria,

48:31.340 --> 48:34.340
and people thought it didn't do sex either until quite recently,

48:34.340 --> 48:36.340
when it turns out it is sexual,

48:36.340 --> 48:38.340
and it turns out that it does have mitochondria too,

48:38.340 --> 48:40.340
just not as we know them.

48:40.340 --> 48:44.340
It has organelles which derive from mitochondria,

48:44.340 --> 48:47.340
called mitosomes.

48:47.340 --> 48:49.340
It's typical of science as well.

48:49.340 --> 48:53.340
It took 25 years of probably about

48:53.340 --> 48:57.340
at least 15 research groups around the world,

48:57.340 --> 48:59.340
not just with jardia,

48:59.340 --> 49:01.340
but with these others as well,

49:01.340 --> 49:04.340
microsperidia, trichomonas, entomebo, monocircumenoides.

49:04.340 --> 49:07.340
These are cells that don't have mitochondria.

49:07.340 --> 49:10.340
For a long time, they were thought to be

49:10.340 --> 49:13.340
an evolutionary intermediate, a living fossil

49:13.340 --> 49:16.340
from very early in eukaryotic evolution,

49:16.340 --> 49:19.340
that were given insight into how complex cells evolved.

49:19.340 --> 49:21.340
It turns out they're not.

49:21.340 --> 49:23.340
They're all derived.

49:23.340 --> 49:26.340
They all had far more complex ancestors in the past,

49:26.340 --> 49:30.340
evolved down in complexity to become more like bacteria.

49:30.340 --> 49:34.340
They all have mitochondria,

49:34.340 --> 49:37.340
and it took 25 years of these research groups

49:37.340 --> 49:39.340
around the world to nail that.

49:39.340 --> 49:41.340
The reason it was done, in part,

49:41.340 --> 49:43.340
is because half of them are parasites,

49:43.340 --> 49:45.340
and so they're of medical interest.

49:45.340 --> 49:47.340
As soon as things become of medical interest,

49:47.340 --> 49:49.340
then people are going to fund you.

49:49.340 --> 49:51.340
If people went to the funders and said,

49:51.340 --> 49:53.340
these are really interesting living fossils

49:53.340 --> 49:55.340
that might give us an insight into

49:55.340 --> 49:57.340
the evolution of complexity,

49:57.340 --> 49:59.340
they're not going to get funded, unfortunately.

49:59.340 --> 50:01.340
If you say it causes explosive diarrhea,

50:01.340 --> 50:03.340
where's the checkbook?

50:03.340 --> 50:05.340
So that's what they said.

50:05.340 --> 50:07.340
They said it causes explosive diarrhea,

50:07.340 --> 50:09.340
and they had 20 years of funding,

50:09.340 --> 50:11.340
and they spent it very wisely

50:11.340 --> 50:14.340
on the early evolution of complexity.

50:14.340 --> 50:17.340
We now know that these are actually

50:17.340 --> 50:21.340
not living fossils, but highly derived.

50:21.340 --> 50:23.340
The one thing that we can take away from it

50:23.340 --> 50:27.340
is they all had mitochondria in the past,

50:27.340 --> 50:29.340
and that's important.

50:29.340 --> 50:31.340
It's important, in part,

50:31.340 --> 50:33.340
because mitochondria, as I said at the beginning,

50:33.340 --> 50:35.340
were bacteria once,

50:35.340 --> 50:38.340
and this was made famous by Lynn Margulis.

50:38.340 --> 50:40.340
Margulis, I should say.

50:40.340 --> 50:43.340
She died of a stroke a couple of years ago.

50:43.340 --> 50:45.340
I only met her once,

50:45.340 --> 50:47.340
and I admired her enormously,

50:47.340 --> 50:49.340
but she had a knack of disagreeing

50:49.340 --> 50:52.340
with everybody about everything,

50:52.340 --> 50:54.340
including me.

50:54.340 --> 50:56.340
Yes, well, that man is...

50:56.340 --> 50:59.340
She was married to Carl Sagan,

50:59.340 --> 51:02.340
and they divorced after a while.

51:02.340 --> 51:05.340
Before she wrote her famous paper in 1967,

51:05.340 --> 51:07.340
they'd already divorced.

51:07.340 --> 51:09.340
I'd love to have heard their breakfast conversations

51:09.340 --> 51:11.340
between those two, but anyway,

51:11.340 --> 51:14.340
she was the person who really nailed the idea

51:14.340 --> 51:16.340
that mitochondria were bacteria once.

51:16.340 --> 51:18.340
She nailed the idea that chloroplasts

51:18.340 --> 51:20.340
derived from bacteria as well,

51:20.340 --> 51:22.340
and she also argued for a long time

51:22.340 --> 51:25.340
that there were lots of other symbioses,

51:25.340 --> 51:27.340
for example, with spirochetes bacteria,

51:27.340 --> 51:29.340
giving rise to the cytoskeleton

51:29.340 --> 51:31.340
and the flagella and so on.

51:31.340 --> 51:34.340
Nobody agrees with her about that.

51:34.340 --> 51:37.340
She was very strong-willed

51:37.340 --> 51:40.340
and disagreed with most people about most things,

51:40.340 --> 51:44.340
but she was bang on for these central ideas

51:44.340 --> 51:46.340
on the origin of the eukaryotic cell,

51:46.340 --> 51:48.340
and the amount of, I suppose you call it,

51:48.340 --> 51:50.340
hate mail now that she got.

51:50.340 --> 51:54.340
If you read the literature from after her paper in 1967

51:54.340 --> 51:56.340
through into the early 70s,

51:56.340 --> 51:58.340
people did not like these ideas at all,

51:58.340 --> 52:01.340
and they wrote really unpleasant diatribes

52:01.340 --> 52:03.340
in the literature.

52:03.340 --> 52:07.340
You can understand why she became very hardened to abuse

52:07.340 --> 52:10.340
and eventually basically believed everybody else

52:10.340 --> 52:12.340
was wrong apart from her.

52:12.340 --> 52:14.340
She was asked once,

52:14.340 --> 52:17.340
why does she enjoy being so controversial,

52:17.340 --> 52:19.340
and her answer was,

52:19.340 --> 52:22.340
I don't think I'm controversial, I think I'm right.

52:22.340 --> 52:25.340
I'm not even sure she used the word think.

52:27.340 --> 52:29.340
So that's Slim Margulis,

52:29.340 --> 52:32.340
and she nailed that mitochondria derived from bacteria,

52:32.340 --> 52:34.340
and we still can't really agree

52:34.340 --> 52:37.340
about exactly which kind of bacteria were they,

52:37.340 --> 52:41.340
but probably something like Rhodobacter that we're seeing there.

52:42.340 --> 52:44.340
So something acquired these bacteria

52:44.340 --> 52:46.340
that went on to become the mitochondria,

52:46.340 --> 52:48.340
and again, there's been no agreement

52:48.340 --> 52:51.340
about what kind of a cell that was until quite recently,

52:51.340 --> 52:54.340
and this is a place called Loki's Castle,

52:54.340 --> 52:57.340
which is just off the coast of Norway,

52:57.340 --> 53:01.340
and a Swedish group have been trawling around

53:01.340 --> 53:03.340
in the muds underneath there

53:03.340 --> 53:06.340
and sequencing everything that they found in those muds.

53:06.340 --> 53:09.340
So we've never even now seen

53:09.340 --> 53:11.340
what these cells actually looked like.

53:11.340 --> 53:13.340
This is what's called metagenomic reconstruction.

53:13.340 --> 53:15.340
So you sequence everything,

53:15.340 --> 53:17.340
and you try and piece together genomes

53:17.340 --> 53:19.340
by effectively matching the ends up,

53:19.340 --> 53:24.340
and eventually you put together the genome of these cells.

53:24.340 --> 53:26.340
There's a certain amount of debate

53:26.340 --> 53:28.340
about whether there's contamination in there,

53:28.340 --> 53:30.340
but it looks broadly true,

53:30.340 --> 53:32.340
and the thing that's really surprising about it is,

53:32.340 --> 53:34.340
you carry it to here, this is another tree,

53:34.340 --> 53:36.340
and right next to them,

53:36.340 --> 53:38.340
so we started out with a Loki archaeata there,

53:38.340 --> 53:40.340
we're discovered at Loki's Castle,

53:40.340 --> 53:42.340
and since then various others have been found,

53:42.340 --> 53:44.340
and they've kept going with this Norse theme,

53:44.340 --> 53:46.340
so now we've got all the Norse gods down there,

53:46.340 --> 53:49.340
we've got the Odin archaeata and the Thor archaeata

53:49.340 --> 53:52.340
and the Heimdal archaeata and so on.

53:52.340 --> 53:54.340
But the thing which is really plain

53:54.340 --> 53:56.340
is that you carry it to our branching

53:56.340 --> 53:58.340
right in the middle of those groups.

53:58.340 --> 54:00.340
So whatever the host cell was that acquired mitochondria

54:00.340 --> 54:02.340
was something pretty similar to this,

54:02.340 --> 54:05.340
and the irony is we don't know what this looks like,

54:05.340 --> 54:07.340
we don't know what kind of a cell it was.

54:07.340 --> 54:09.340
Some people say it was a primitive phagasite

54:09.340 --> 54:11.340
that kind of tried to eat things.

54:11.340 --> 54:14.340
Other people, including me, say,

54:14.340 --> 54:16.340
oh no, it wasn't, it was an autotrofe,

54:16.340 --> 54:18.340
it used hydrogen gas.

54:18.340 --> 54:21.340
I don't think we can really be very sure yet

54:21.340 --> 54:23.340
what kind of a cell it was,

54:23.340 --> 54:26.340
but it was probably basically a fairly simple cell.

54:26.340 --> 54:31.340
And so this is another tree,

54:31.340 --> 54:33.340
which I think is beautiful,

54:33.340 --> 54:36.340
this is from one of the most, I think, brilliant biologists

54:36.340 --> 54:39.340
operating today, a guy called Bill Martin.

54:39.340 --> 54:43.340
He also has a knack of winding people up.

54:43.340 --> 54:47.340
And this tree goes back to 1998.

54:47.340 --> 54:50.340
And it's remarkable for several reasons.

54:50.340 --> 54:53.340
One of them is that it's now more right than it was then.

54:53.340 --> 54:55.340
So in 1998 when he put this forward,

54:55.340 --> 54:58.340
I think most people must have thought he was bonkers.

54:58.340 --> 55:01.340
Look down here, we have two separate origins

55:01.340 --> 55:03.340
from a hydrothermal vent.

55:03.340 --> 55:06.340
So the bacteria on the archaea.

55:06.340 --> 55:09.340
I haven't really gone into the details of that.

55:09.340 --> 55:12.340
When I first heard him say that in 2002,

55:12.340 --> 55:14.340
I thought he was completely bonkers.

55:14.340 --> 55:17.340
I now think he was absolutely right.

55:17.340 --> 55:20.340
I haven't really had time to go into why they would,

55:20.340 --> 55:22.340
so they share a common ancestor,

55:22.340 --> 55:25.340
but down inside the vents.

55:25.340 --> 55:27.340
The other thing which is really clear on here

55:27.340 --> 55:31.340
is he has a kind of genomic merger going on.

55:31.340 --> 55:34.340
So genes from the archaea and genes from the bacteria

55:34.340 --> 55:37.340
are fusing together here to form the eukaryotes.

55:37.340 --> 55:41.340
And this is a singular endosymbiosis.

55:41.340 --> 55:44.340
This one is the chloroplasts.

55:44.340 --> 55:47.340
So this is not really the same as Lynn Margulis

55:47.340 --> 55:49.340
who had lots of these things going on

55:49.340 --> 55:51.340
in all kinds of different cell lines.

55:51.340 --> 55:54.340
This was a singular event that gave rise to eukaryotic cells.

55:54.340 --> 55:57.340
And later on, the acquisition of chloroplasts

55:57.340 --> 56:00.340
gave rise to plants, but it didn't change anything really

56:00.340 --> 56:02.340
about the big structure of eukaryotic evolution.

56:02.340 --> 56:05.340
Plants are the same type of cells that we have,

56:05.340 --> 56:08.340
except with chloroplasts added in and a vacuol,

56:08.340 --> 56:10.340
but we're basically the same.

56:10.340 --> 56:15.340
So Bill has this singular origin of complex life.

56:15.340 --> 56:18.340
Now a lot of people really hate this idea,

56:18.340 --> 56:22.340
and I think it's in part because we don't really like the idea

56:22.340 --> 56:24.340
of freak accidents in science.

56:24.340 --> 56:27.340
It kind of almost puts itself beyond science.

56:27.340 --> 56:31.340
We can't study statistically an accident, a singularity,

56:31.340 --> 56:35.340
but you can think about it in a very productive way.

56:35.340 --> 56:38.340
If this was the origin of the eukaryotic cell,

56:38.340 --> 56:41.340
and it started something like this,

56:41.340 --> 56:43.340
this is the only example that we know of

56:43.340 --> 56:46.340
of bacteria living inside another bacterial cell.

56:46.340 --> 56:48.340
So there's plenty of bacteria living inside

56:48.340 --> 56:51.340
our own type of cell, eukaryotic cells,

56:51.340 --> 56:56.340
but it's really rare for bacteria to be inside another bacterial cell.

56:56.340 --> 56:58.340
This is not a phagocyte.

56:58.340 --> 57:01.340
It didn't engulf the cell to get in there.

57:01.340 --> 57:03.340
It's got a cell wall around it.

57:03.340 --> 57:05.340
It's actually a cyanobacterium,

57:05.340 --> 57:07.340
and you can see the photosynthetic membranes here.

57:07.340 --> 57:09.340
So we don't know what they're doing there.

57:09.340 --> 57:11.340
This actually is an old discovery.

57:11.340 --> 57:13.340
This is from 1979,

57:13.340 --> 57:16.340
when they were still called blue-green algae in those days.

57:16.340 --> 57:18.340
And blue-green algae really refers to eukaryotes,

57:18.340 --> 57:21.340
so everybody ignored that paper for 20 years

57:21.340 --> 57:24.340
until it turned out they were actually bacteria

57:24.340 --> 57:26.340
with bacteria inside,

57:26.340 --> 57:32.340
and so this speaks more about the whole sweep of evolution.

57:32.340 --> 57:34.340
Why would that make a difference?

57:34.340 --> 57:36.340
Well, the cells that are living inside,

57:36.340 --> 57:38.340
they are bacteria.

57:38.340 --> 57:39.340
They are cells.

57:39.340 --> 57:40.340
They've got their own agenda.

57:40.340 --> 57:41.340
They want to grow.

57:41.340 --> 57:42.340
They want to divide.

57:42.340 --> 57:43.340
They want to...

57:43.340 --> 57:49.340
There's a lovely quote from Jack Monogh,

57:49.340 --> 57:53.340
who said that the dream of every cell is to become two cells.

57:53.340 --> 57:57.340
And so that's what these guys are dreaming about in here.

57:57.340 --> 58:01.340
They're thinking, how am I going to double?

58:01.340 --> 58:04.340
And the way that they do it,

58:04.340 --> 58:06.340
if you imagine a population of bacteria,

58:06.340 --> 58:10.340
and they're all growing frantically,

58:10.340 --> 58:12.340
and the speed at which they grow

58:12.340 --> 58:15.340
depends on the speed at which they can copy their genome

58:15.340 --> 58:16.340
as much as anything else.

58:16.340 --> 58:19.340
And so the smaller the genome is, the faster they can grow.

58:19.340 --> 58:23.340
It tells that if there's something about the environment

58:23.340 --> 58:26.340
that means they don't need this gene now,

58:26.340 --> 58:29.340
it's not useful and they lose it, they delete it,

58:29.340 --> 58:31.340
then they can probably grow a little bit faster

58:31.340 --> 58:33.340
because their genome is just a little bit smaller.

58:33.340 --> 58:35.340
And over a couple of days, bacteria,

58:35.340 --> 58:38.340
their growth rate does depend on that kind of factor.

58:38.340 --> 58:40.340
But then the environment changes again

58:40.340 --> 58:42.340
and whatever it was that that gene did,

58:42.340 --> 58:43.340
you need it again now.

58:43.340 --> 58:46.340
And so they pick it up.

58:46.340 --> 58:48.340
What bacteria do is they pick up genes

58:48.340 --> 58:49.340
called lateral gene transfer.

58:49.340 --> 58:51.340
It's like passing loose change around.

58:51.340 --> 58:53.340
They acquire it again

58:53.340 --> 58:55.340
and before you know it, you're back where you were.

58:55.340 --> 58:57.340
But if you've got a same population of bacteria

58:57.340 --> 58:59.340
living inside another cell,

58:59.340 --> 59:01.340
they do the same thing.

59:01.340 --> 59:03.340
They throw away genes that they don't need.

59:03.340 --> 59:06.340
Imagine that those genes are for making a cell wall,

59:06.340 --> 59:09.340
and you're living inside another cell,

59:09.340 --> 59:13.340
and you don't need a cell wall for protection inside another cell

59:13.340 --> 59:16.340
or for preventing yourself exploding

59:16.340 --> 59:19.340
with the difference in pressure between the outside and inside.

59:19.340 --> 59:21.340
So you lose those genes, you grow a little bit faster,

59:21.340 --> 59:23.340
you come to dominate the population.

59:23.340 --> 59:26.340
But so long as the cell doesn't die that you're living in,

59:26.340 --> 59:27.340
you'll be all right.

59:27.340 --> 59:29.340
You never need those genes again.

59:29.340 --> 59:33.340
And so there's a tendency for bacterial parasites

59:33.340 --> 59:36.340
to lose genes and to become simpler.

59:36.340 --> 59:38.340
And not just bacterial parasites,

59:38.340 --> 59:41.340
we see the same thing with Jardier and so on.

59:41.340 --> 59:44.340
And a very nice example is Rickettsia,

59:44.340 --> 59:46.340
which a few years ago people thought

59:46.340 --> 59:48.340
was very closely related to mitochondria.

59:48.340 --> 59:51.340
It's probably not so closely related.

59:51.340 --> 59:53.340
But it's still a beautiful example.

59:53.340 --> 59:58.340
It was the cause of time that wiped out the armies of Napoleon

59:58.340 --> 01:00:01.340
on his retreat from Moscow.

01:00:01.340 --> 01:00:05.340
And it's spread by these ticks.

01:00:05.340 --> 01:00:07.340
And it's a bacterium.

01:00:07.340 --> 01:00:11.340
Here it is invading a large eukaryotic cell.

01:00:11.340 --> 01:00:13.340
I think it's actually a kidney cell.

01:00:14.340 --> 01:00:16.340
And the one thing about it which stands out

01:00:16.340 --> 01:00:18.340
is it's got a tiny genome.

01:00:18.340 --> 01:00:20.340
It's around about one megabase genome.

01:00:20.340 --> 01:00:22.340
And that's true for all of these things.

01:00:22.340 --> 01:00:24.340
I'm not just hand-waving here.

01:00:24.340 --> 01:00:29.340
This is the range of genome sizes of free-living bacteria.

01:00:29.340 --> 01:00:32.340
It goes up to around about 12 megabases now.

01:00:32.340 --> 01:00:36.340
This guy, T. Ryan Gregory, did a lot of work on genome sizes.

01:00:36.340 --> 01:00:39.340
And down at this other end,

01:00:39.340 --> 01:00:43.340
these are the parasites and the endosymbionts

01:00:43.340 --> 01:00:45.340
and the obligate symbionts.

01:00:45.340 --> 01:00:49.340
They're pretty much down at less than one megabase of DNA.

01:00:49.340 --> 01:00:51.340
So just for comparison's sake,

01:00:51.340 --> 01:00:54.340
we have 3,000 megabases of DNA.

01:00:54.340 --> 01:00:59.340
The largest bacterial genome is 12 megabases of DNA.

01:00:59.340 --> 01:01:02.340
And some large algae, like eudlina,

01:01:02.340 --> 01:01:06.340
are up to 100,000 megabases of DNA.

01:01:06.340 --> 01:01:08.340
So we have quite constrained genomes

01:01:08.340 --> 01:01:10.340
in comparison with some single cell.

01:01:10.340 --> 01:01:13.340
The largest one is a thing called Amoeba W,

01:01:13.340 --> 01:01:15.340
which was miscountered.

01:01:15.340 --> 01:01:18.340
It was originally 670,000 megabases.

01:01:18.340 --> 01:01:21.340
It's come down to 150,000 last count.

01:01:21.340 --> 01:01:25.340
But still, it's very, very substantially bigger

01:01:25.340 --> 01:01:28.340
than our own genome.

01:01:28.340 --> 01:01:31.340
But what happens with these bacteria that live in other cells?

01:01:31.340 --> 01:01:33.340
They lose genes. They become simpler.

01:01:33.340 --> 01:01:35.340
They whittle away.

01:01:35.340 --> 01:01:39.340
And that's what ended up with the mitochondria.

01:01:39.340 --> 01:01:42.340
All these mitochondria that we have

01:01:42.340 --> 01:01:45.340
in millions of billions of copies,

01:01:45.340 --> 01:01:47.340
they all have genomes of their own,

01:01:47.340 --> 01:01:49.340
and they're passed on down the maternal line

01:01:49.340 --> 01:01:52.340
from mother to son.

01:01:52.340 --> 01:01:55.340
My kids don't have my mitochondria.

01:01:55.340 --> 01:01:57.340
They have my wife's mitochondria.

01:01:57.340 --> 01:02:01.340
It's a very strange arrangement that I won't go into now.

01:02:01.340 --> 01:02:04.340
What it means is that if you want to be bigger,

01:02:04.340 --> 01:02:06.340
more complex and spend more energy,

01:02:06.340 --> 01:02:09.340
it's not just a case of having a larger surface area.

01:02:09.340 --> 01:02:11.340
You've got a whole unit here.

01:02:11.340 --> 01:02:14.340
That unit has some genes, which in some way control respiration.

01:02:14.340 --> 01:02:17.340
It's got the protein building factories, the ribosomes.

01:02:17.340 --> 01:02:19.340
It's a unit, and if you want to expand,

01:02:19.340 --> 01:02:21.340
you just make more units.

01:02:21.340 --> 01:02:23.340
You have more mitochondria.

01:02:23.340 --> 01:02:25.340
But it's not just that you're increasing the surface area.

01:02:25.340 --> 01:02:27.340
You've got genomes with each one.

01:02:27.340 --> 01:02:30.340
And that allows you to expand up on a massive scale.

01:02:30.340 --> 01:02:33.340
And the person who's, I think, done more on this side,

01:02:33.340 --> 01:02:36.340
again, going back to the early 1990s,

01:02:36.340 --> 01:02:39.340
John Allen has been arguing that they require genes

01:02:39.340 --> 01:02:41.340
to control respiration.

01:02:41.340 --> 01:02:43.340
And still, I would say,

01:02:43.340 --> 01:02:46.340
the majority of the field is not persuaded that he's correct.

01:02:46.340 --> 01:02:48.340
He is correct, I'm sure of that.

01:02:48.340 --> 01:02:51.340
But it takes an awful long time in science

01:02:51.340 --> 01:02:54.340
for sometimes the simplest ideas to catch on.

01:02:54.340 --> 01:02:57.340
Most people just don't really care very much, I'm afraid.

01:02:57.340 --> 01:03:00.340
But it's the difference.

01:03:00.340 --> 01:03:03.340
That they can, to become a very large cell,

01:03:03.340 --> 01:03:06.340
you just scale up mitochondria.

01:03:06.340 --> 01:03:10.340
So this is a giant bacterium, and there are a few around.

01:03:10.340 --> 01:03:14.340
These little white dots here are the copies of the complete genome.

01:03:14.340 --> 01:03:17.340
So the giant bacteria that do exist,

01:03:17.340 --> 01:03:20.340
it seems that they also need genes to control respiration.

01:03:20.340 --> 01:03:22.340
And this is the edge of the cell,

01:03:22.340 --> 01:03:25.340
and this is the plasma membrane where respiration is taking place.

01:03:25.340 --> 01:03:29.340
And they have as many as 200,000 copies of the complete genome.

01:03:29.340 --> 01:03:32.340
And each genome is a normal-sized bacterial genome

01:03:32.340 --> 01:03:35.340
with three megabases of DNA in it.

01:03:35.340 --> 01:03:37.340
And this is a eukaryotic cell.

01:03:37.340 --> 01:03:40.340
The blue is the nucleus where it's the main gene depot.

01:03:40.340 --> 01:03:44.340
And all these little, the green spots here

01:03:44.340 --> 01:03:47.340
are the mitochondrial DNA.

01:03:47.340 --> 01:03:52.340
So there are hundreds or thousands of copies of mitochondrial DNA.

01:03:52.340 --> 01:03:54.340
So the difference between these two cells

01:03:54.340 --> 01:03:57.340
is not that this cell has an awful lot more DNA than that cell,

01:03:57.340 --> 01:03:59.340
they actually have a similar amount.

01:03:59.340 --> 01:04:02.340
It's that in that case it's got a kind of genomic symmetry.

01:04:02.340 --> 01:04:05.340
There's thousands of copies of the same genome,

01:04:05.340 --> 01:04:07.340
exactly the same genome.

01:04:07.340 --> 01:04:10.340
Whereas here we've got one massive nuclear genome

01:04:10.340 --> 01:04:13.340
which is supported energetically by this kind of end point.

01:04:13.340 --> 01:04:16.340
Thousands of mitochondrial genomes which have whittled down

01:04:16.340 --> 01:04:19.340
and become smaller and smaller and more and more streamlined.

01:04:19.340 --> 01:04:21.340
So all the mitochondria, effectively,

01:04:21.340 --> 01:04:24.340
it gives us multi-bacterial power without the bacterial overheads.

01:04:24.340 --> 01:04:27.340
And that's what allows all those overheads

01:04:27.340 --> 01:04:30.340
can go into supporting a massive nucleus with full of genes.

01:04:30.340 --> 01:04:34.340
At least it's the raw material for natural selection to operate on.

01:04:34.340 --> 01:04:36.340
And so we have a kind of genomic asymmetry.

01:04:36.340 --> 01:04:39.340
And to me that's the real difference between bacteria

01:04:39.340 --> 01:04:41.340
and large complex cells.

01:04:41.340 --> 01:04:42.340
We've got two genomes.

01:04:42.340 --> 01:04:44.340
There isn't such a thing as the human genome,

01:04:44.340 --> 01:04:47.340
there are human genomes, the mitochondrial genome

01:04:47.340 --> 01:04:48.340
and the nuclear genome.

01:04:48.340 --> 01:04:50.340
This is the last slide.

01:04:51.340 --> 01:04:55.340
Why then is complex life so rare?

01:04:55.340 --> 01:04:57.340
Why did it only happen once on Earth?

01:04:57.340 --> 01:05:01.340
And would it only happen rarely elsewhere in the universe?

01:05:01.340 --> 01:05:05.340
There's a double bottleneck here.

01:05:05.340 --> 01:05:09.340
One of them we have to get bacterium into another bacterial type cell

01:05:09.340 --> 01:05:14.340
to break down this issue with membranes and scaling.

01:05:14.340 --> 01:05:19.340
So you've got to have cells within cells to be able to scale up.

01:05:19.340 --> 01:05:21.340
But those cells have their own agenda.

01:05:21.340 --> 01:05:26.340
You have what's called conflict, levels of selection conflict

01:05:26.340 --> 01:05:31.340
that the bacteria inside want to grow fast

01:05:31.340 --> 01:05:34.340
and perhaps make their host cell fuse with other cells

01:05:34.340 --> 01:05:35.340
or whatever they want to do.

01:05:35.340 --> 01:05:37.340
The host cell itself wants to keep them under control

01:05:37.340 --> 01:05:38.340
and bleed off the energy

01:05:38.340 --> 01:05:41.340
but they don't want them replicating at any old speed.

01:05:41.340 --> 01:05:43.340
Chances of it going wrong is really high.

01:05:43.340 --> 01:05:47.340
And maybe this is why we don't see any surviving intermediates.

01:05:47.340 --> 01:05:50.340
Maybe they all died because it was a pretty dodgy situation

01:05:50.340 --> 01:05:54.340
for a long period of time or even a short period of time.

01:05:54.340 --> 01:05:57.340
It's just that this is a long evolutionary distance.

01:05:57.340 --> 01:06:00.340
Regardless of whether what I'm telling you is right or not,

01:06:00.340 --> 01:06:02.340
this long evolutionary distance,

01:06:02.340 --> 01:06:05.340
there are no evolutionary intermediates that have ever been found.

01:06:05.340 --> 01:06:08.340
And so all of this complexity in this type of cell

01:06:08.340 --> 01:06:10.340
and I would like to leave you with this thought,

01:06:10.340 --> 01:06:15.340
we have no idea yet at least the difference between ideas

01:06:15.340 --> 01:06:17.340
and serious scientific knowledge

01:06:17.340 --> 01:06:21.340
where we can say that there have been experiments done and real data,

01:06:21.340 --> 01:06:25.340
how any of this complexity of eukaryotic cells arose.

01:06:25.340 --> 01:06:28.340
And if we want to understand medicine and what goes wrong in our own bodies

01:06:28.340 --> 01:06:33.340
and we don't understand why these parts arose in the first place,

01:06:33.340 --> 01:06:37.340
what were the evolutionary driving forces that made them evolve,

01:06:37.340 --> 01:06:41.340
how can we really understand ourselves and medicine?

01:06:41.340 --> 01:06:46.340
And if this starts out with mitochondria in a very simple cell

01:06:46.340 --> 01:06:48.340
with none of that complexity,

01:06:48.340 --> 01:06:53.340
the nice thing from my point of view is that perhaps all of this complexity arose

01:06:53.340 --> 01:06:57.340
and the reason that we share such similar cells with plants and with algae

01:06:57.340 --> 01:07:01.340
is not that we were all adapting to different external environments,

01:07:01.340 --> 01:07:04.340
but we all were adapting to the same internal environment,

01:07:04.340 --> 01:07:06.340
the problem of having cells living inside us.

01:07:06.340 --> 01:07:09.340
And it's that that drove all of this complexity.

01:07:09.340 --> 01:07:11.340
And once it became a stable system,

01:07:11.340 --> 01:07:15.340
then eukaryotes could spread out and take over the rest of the world.

01:07:15.340 --> 01:07:18.340
And with that, I'd like to say thank you very much.

01:07:18.340 --> 01:07:20.340
This work has been done by many people,

01:07:20.340 --> 01:07:26.340
and it's great fun having a lab with so many bright young people coming through it.

01:07:26.340 --> 01:07:28.340
It's an inspiration for me. Thank you very much.

